At the same time, however, the majority of Italians regard divorce as one of the principal problems besetting contemporary society. This is primarily because the significant number of Italian marriages that end in divorce often gives rise to conflicts about children, seldom a cause for confrontation in pre-1970 Italy.

Many Italian parents regard marriage and childbearing as the highest values, and the news of a partner’s affair evokes great emotional and psychological reactions. It also prompts a bitter struggle over the custody of children, as indicated in this finding from The Survey Milan-based Domus reported in 2003:

The majority of divorcees admitted that any recovering of the relationship was merely that: a recovery of the relationship… Domestic violence, according to 40% of women, was the Hamlet-like catalyst that led to a disposition to either reconcile, or separate [from their husbands]. This coincides with the responses given to the question: which episodes caused the most soul searching: 53% of respondents felt that it was solely the solution, or discontinuation, of the relationship itself that they weighed in accordance with circumstances – far more than those who answered “everything being equal, declination of their own mentality and/or their partner’s attitude”.
